\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textit {Memorandum from the Secretary of Defense, ``Unleashing U.S.\ Military Drone Dominance''} (10 July 2025, signed by the Secretary of Defense) directs the rapid proliferation of Group~1 and Group~2 \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} across all \pdftooltip {\oldac {dod}}{\acl {dod}} units. Issued in support of Executive Order 14307 (``Unleashing American Drone Dominance,'' 6 June 2025), it rescinds the 2021 \pdftooltip {\oldac {dod}}{\acl {dod}} guidance implementing \pdftooltip {\oldac {ndaa}}{\acl {ndaa}} FY2020 {\S }848 and the 2022 Blue \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} exception-to-policy memorandum, replacing both with streamlined authorities and procurement directives.}}{49}{section*.294}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{Key provisions relevant to this SOP include:}}{49}{section*.295}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Delegated Authority to O-6 Commanders:} O-6 commanders or equivalents may grant authority to operate (ATO) and may procure, test, and train with small \pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}} compliant with statutory limitations. This authority may not be further delegated. This delegation informed the SOP's approval and command authority framework.}}{49}{section*.296}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Blue List Compliance:} All \pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}} must comply with the Blue List maintained by the \pdftooltip {\oldac {diu}}{\acl {diu}} (transferring to \pdftooltip {\oldac {dcma}}{\acl {dcma}} by January 2026), which catalogues \pdftooltip {\oldac {dod}}{\acl {dod}}-approved \pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}}, components, and software. The SOP's procurement and vetting procedures align with Blue List requirements.}}{49}{section*.297}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Cybersecurity --- Closed-Loop Networks:} All small \pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}} must remain in closed-loop cyber networks, cordoned from \pdftooltip {\oldac {dod}}{\acl {dod}} networks. This requirement reinforced the SOP's cybersecurity and data-handling provisions.}}{49}{section*.298}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Airworthiness and Material Release Exemptions:} The Secretaries of the Military Departments shall determine airworthiness and material release requirements, exempting Group~1 and Group~2 \pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}} with few exceptions. This exemption shaped the SOP's streamlined airworthiness approach for small \pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}}.}}{49}{section*.299}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Training Delegation:} Group~1--2 \pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}} operator training and qualifications are delegated to the Military Departments with minimal additional medical standards. \pdftooltip {\oldac {dod}}{\acl {dod}} entities outside the Military Departments shall adhere to standards prescribed by the Secretary of the Army. This delegation underpins the SOP's operator certification and medical standards.}}{49}{section*.300}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Covered Foreign Entity Restrictions:} The memo reaffirms \pdftooltip {\oldac {ndaa}}{\acl {ndaa}} FY2020 {\S }848, FY2023 {\S }817, and the American Security Drone Act (FY2024 {\S \S }1821--1825), permitting only limited procurement from covered foreign entities for research, training, testing, electronic warfare analysis, or counter-\pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}} development. These statutory constraints informed the SOP's procurement restrictions and cybersecurity risk-mitigation procedures.}}{49}{section*.301}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Installation Commander Responsibilities:} Installation commanders will integrate drones against their unique installation restrictions, working with the \pdftooltip {\oldac {faa}}{\acl {faa}} to remove inappropriate range restrictions and expand spectrum approval. This directive informed the SOP's airspace coordination and installation-specific operating area provisions.}}{49}{section*.302}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Consumable Classification:} Group~1 and Group~2 \pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}} will be accounted for as consumable commodities, not durable property. This classification influenced the SOP's property accountability and logistics procedures.}}{49}{section*.303}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textit {Army Regulation 95--1, Flight Regulations} (22 March 2018), Appendix~D, establishes regulatory guidance for Group~1 \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} (0.55--20\,lbs) operated by personnel other than \pdftooltip {\oldac {mos}}{\acl {mos}}-qualified unmanned aircraft operators. Appendix~D is the primary Army regulatory authority governing \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} training, qualification, currency, airspace usage, and crew requirements.}}{49}{section*.304}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{Key provisions drawn upon in this SOP include:}}{49}{section*.305}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Personnel Eligibility ({\S }D--2):} Authorized \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} operators include Regular Army, \pdftooltip {\oldac {usar}}{\acl {usar}}, \pdftooltip {\oldac {arng}}{\acl {arng}}, and Army civilian employees who meet qualification, training, evaluation, and currency requirements and the medical standard of AR~40--501 (without a Class~IV physical). Government contractors require written authorization from the owning \pdftooltip {\oldac {acom}}{\acl {acom}}/\pdftooltip {\oldac {ascc}}{\acl {ascc}}/\pdftooltip {\oldac {dru}}{\acl {dru}}/\pdftooltip {\oldac {arng}}{\acl {arng}}. These eligibility criteria informed the SOP's operator qualification requirements.}}{50}{section*.306}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Training Program and Currency ({\S \S }D--3, D--4):} The \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} \pdftooltip {\oldac {atp}}{\acl {atp}} and currency requirements follow the appropriate \pdftooltip {\oldac {mtl}}{\acl {mtl}}. Lapsed currency requires a \pdftooltip {\oldac {pfe}}{\acl {pfe}}; simulators may not reestablish currency. These requirements informed the SOP's training and currency framework (subject to the D--10 exemption discussed below).}}{50}{section*.307}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Airspace Usage ({\S }D--7):} \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} operations comply with paragraph~2--11 of AR~95--1 and applicable \pdftooltip {\oldac {faa}}{\acl {faa}} orders. \pdftooltip {\oldac {dod}}{\acl {dod}} \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} weighing 0.55--20\,lbs may operate in Class~G airspace below 1,200\,ft \pdftooltip {\oldac {agl}}{\acl {agl}} within \pdftooltip {\oldac {vlos}}{\acl {vlos}} of the operator or a certified observer, provided the \pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}} remains more than 5\,miles from any civil airport or heliport. \pdftooltip {\oldac {notam}}{\acl {notam}} publication is required no later than 24~hours in advance for non-recurring operations; standing ``blanket'' \pdftooltip {\oldac {notam}}{\acl {notam}}s are prohibited. These airspace provisions directly shaped the SOP's default operating conditions and \pdftooltip {\oldac {notam}}{\acl {notam}} procedures.}}{50}{section*.308}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Minimum Crew ({\S }D--8):} The minimum crew is one qualified operator unless the operator's manual specifies otherwise. This requirement informed the SOP's minimum crew composition.}}{50}{section*.309}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Certification of Operators and Master Trainers ({\S }D--9):} Master Trainers designated by the first O--6 in the chain of command certify new operators at home station. Qualification courses are conducted at \pdftooltip {\oldac {tradoc}}{\acl {tradoc}}-approved locations. These provisions informed the SOP's operator certification pathway (subject to the D--10 exemption discussed below).}}{50}{section*.310}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Nonstandard \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} with a Non-Tactical Mission ({\S }D--10):} This paragraph is the foundational regulatory exemption for \projectmars {}. See discussion below.}}{50}{section*.311}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{Paragraph~D--10 of AR~95--1 is the single most important regulatory provision enabling \projectmars {}. It provides that Group~1 \pdftooltip {\oldac {uas}}{\acl {uas}} procured per Chapter~9 of AR~95--1 for non-tactical missions---explicitly including ``research and academic activities within Army research laboratories, RDECOM, military academies''---are \textbf {exempt from the qualification, evaluation, and currency requirements} of the regulation. The owning organization retains responsibility for safe operations and compliance with applicable \pdftooltip {\oldac {faa}}{\acl {faa}} circulars.}}{50}{section*.312}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{For \projectmars {}, this means:}}{50}{section*.313}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Exemption from AR~95--1 operator qualification, evaluation, and currency:} \pdftooltip {\oldac {usma}}{\acl {usma}} operators need not complete the \pdftooltip {\oldac {tradoc}}{\acl {tradoc}}-approved \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} operator qualification course, semi-annual proficiency and readiness tests ({\S }D--5), or standard \pdftooltip {\oldac {atp}}{\acl {atp}} currency requirements ({\S }D--4). This exemption---reinforced by ALARACT~080/2024 and West Point Policy Memorandum MR-25-02 ({\S }5.c)---is the basis for the SOP's locally developed operator certification framework.}}{50}{section*.314}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Continued \pdftooltip {\oldac {faa}}{\acl {faa}} compliance:} The exemption does not relieve \pdftooltip {\oldac {usma}}{\acl {usma}} of \pdftooltip {\oldac {faa}}{\acl {faa}} obligations. Operators must still hold an \pdftooltip {\oldac {faa}}{\acl {faa}} Remote Pilot Certificate (14~CFR Part~107), register \pdftooltip {\oldac {suas}}{\acl {suas}} with the \pdftooltip {\oldac {faa}}{\acl {faa}}, and comply with all applicable \pdftooltip {\oldac {faa}}{\acl {faa}} airspace rules and waivers. The SOP's \pdftooltip {\oldac {faa}}{\acl {faa}} compliance requirements derive from this continued obligation.}}{50}{section*.315}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\textbf {Safe operations responsibility:} \pdftooltip {\oldac {usma}}{\acl {usma}} as the owning organization bears full responsibility for establishing and enforcing safe operating procedures---which is the central purpose of this SOP.}}{50}{section*.316}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\Cref {fig:ar95-1-d10} reproduces Paragraph~D--10 from AR~95--1 in its entirety.}}{50}{section*.317}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(claude): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{AR 95--1, Paragraph D--10: Nonstandard small unmanned aircraft systems with a non-tactical mission (22 March 2018).}}{51}{section*.319}%
